Goal:

Create a raw disk image installer, which dumps an image to a disk.
With this setup, we have two stages during installation:

1. Dump a prebuild disk image to harddisk
   - This does not contain any modifications of the content of the image!
2. Personalization of the OS during first boot
   - Resize image
   - Create additional partitions
   - Create users, set passwords, install ssh keys
   - Configure and enable services
   ...

For the second part we have ignition, combustion and cloud-init, depending on the kind of image.

For the first part we need something new, this raw-disk-image-installer:
- Small, simple, fast
- Low memory usage (needs to work with 1GB RAM, preferable 512 MB) => not possible since we run out of memory (PXE, UEFI HTTP(S))
  - Edge Systems
  - Big embedded devices
- Robust
  - Always check for errors everywhere including error handling
  - Always print errors or save in log files accessible to the user
- User-friendly
  - Pre-defined/pre-filled values that can be customized
- Secure
  - No remote ssh login with default user/password?
  - Strict certificate checks e.g. for https?
  - compare hashes and gpg signatures
  - ...
- Single disk setup (root and data on same disk)
- Multi disk setup
  - Special case, root and data on separate disks. This is "Single disk setup" where the data will be generated at first boot, e.g. systemd-repart and combustion
- Remote disks:
  - iSCSI
  - FCoE
- MD RAID setups
  - RAID 1 for the OS
  - RAID 5 for data or both on RAID 5)
- Multipath
- Network setup without DHCP available (similar to linuxrc netsetup=XXX)
  - Provide static IP
  - Propose network setup for installation, let admin adjust it
- Automatable/configurable
- Boot installer via:
  - ISO
  - USB stick
  - PXE/iPXE/zPXE (s390x)
  - UEFI HTTP(S) Boot
- Local or remote image source (USB, ISO, network via https, http, ftp, tftp, local file)
  - Air gapped
  - Proxy access
  - IPv4 and IPv6
- Support compressed and uncompressed images
- Deploy config for ignition/combustion/cloud-init
  - done via "add_extra_partition script"

